ctioning within a complex society based on kinship ties. Exploring the ways in which sexual identity is constructed, these authors discuss, for example, how going out for coffee embodies dominant ideas about female sexuality, moral virtue, and autonomy; why men in a Lesbos village maintain elaborate friendships with nonfamily members while the women do not; why young housewives often participate in conflict-resolution rituals; and how the dominant role of mature married householders is challenged by unmarried persons who emphasize spontaneity and personal autonomy. This collection demonstrates that kinship and gender identities in Greece are not unitary and fixed: kinship is organized in several highly specific forms, and gender identities are plural, competing, antagonistic, and are continually being redefined by contexts and social change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFriendshipzGreece. 0aKinshipzGreece. 0aMarriagezGreece. 0aSex rolezGreece. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aBoulay, ]uliet du, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCowan, Jane K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDanforth, Loring M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubisch, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerzfeld, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJust, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoizos, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoizos, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPapataxiarchis, Evthmios, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPapataxiarchis, Evthymios, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.